{"source_key":"sha256-a74ceb5e1c9633ab993c14c11d587d71","record_index":5298,"record_hash":"sha256:53bb989f48e9147fd271be28fd9215622c2cc31b92a6a3d7341ce9a9efbdf3e6","timestamp":"2026-05-21T19:30:52.949Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"Use a Claude Code `Stop` hook and point it at `but agentlog hook --agent claude`.\n\nProject-local setup:\n\n```sh\nmkdir -p .claude\n$EDITOR .claude/settings.json\n```\n\nPut this in `.claude/settings.json`:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"hooks\": {\n    \"Stop\": [\n      {\n        \"hooks\": [\n          {\n            \"type\": \"command\",\n            \"command\": \"but agentlog hook --agent claude\"\n          }\n        ]\n      }\n    ]\n  }\n}\n```\n\nThat’s it. Claude sends hook JSON on stdin, including `transcript_path` and `cwd`; `but agentlog hook` reads those, captures the transcript, and silently starts `but agentlog sync` when metadata changed.\n\nUse `~/.claude/settings.json` instead if you want it global for all projects. I’d start project-local so you don’t capture random Claude sessions everywhere.\n\nQuick checks:\n\n```sh\nbut agentlog hook --help\n```\n\nThen in Claude Code, run:\n\n```text\n/hooks\n```\n\nand confirm the `Stop` hook is visible.\n\nSources: Claude’s hook docs say project hooks live in `.claude/settings.json`, user hooks in `~/.claude/settings.json`, and command hooks receive JSON on stdin with fields like `transcript_path` and `cwd`: [Claude Code hooks reference](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/hooks), [hooks guide](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/hooks-guide).","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-21T19:30:52.949Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}